Data science challenge

The competition will take place in the Data Science Challenges platform, which is available at the following link:

https://data-science-challenges.unibocconi.it

You must log in with your credentials to enter the competition. There, you will find a copy of the training and test datasets. However, a copy of the data is also available on the github repository and can be downloaded using the code provided in this notebook.

Dataset

The dataset is sourced from the NYC Taxi and Limousine Commission. Each observation corresponds to a ride taken in a yellow taxi cab. Although data for billions of rides across several years are available, we will focus on a subset of data from May 2015. The raw data has been partially cleaned and merged with spatial data from the NYC Department of City Planning.

The data has been filtered to include only transactions paid for with a credit card. Variables include the hour and day of the week the cab was picked up, neighborhood codes for the neighborhood tabulation area where the cab was picked up, and the neighborhood where the passenger was dropped off.

Assignment rules and evaluation criteria

The variable of interest is the tip amount (response variable), i.e. the amount tipped to the driver.

Submissions are evaluated using the Mean Absolute Error (MAE) between the predicted response and the observed target (response), that is

\[ \text{MAE} = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n} |y_i - \hat{y}_i |. \] In this competition, you will be evaluated based on:

  • A .pdf report (at most three pages) that you will need to enclose in the data competition platform before the deadline;
  • The final MAE score on the test set. Please note that only the last submission is evaluated.

The training, public, and private datasets correspond to roughly 70%, 5%, and 25% of the original data, respectively. These subsets have been randomly sampled.

The winning teams will present their work in class.

Columns

A data dictionary of the raw dataset is available here. Below, you can find a description of the actual columns. The raw data and further documentation can be found at this link.

  • response: The response variable, i.e. the tip amount in US dollars
  • weight: constant variable that can be removed because the evaluation score is not weighted
  • pickup_hour: Hour of the pick-up
  • pickup_month: Month of the pick-up (always May)
  • pickup_week: Week of the pick-up
  • pickup_doy: Day of the year of the pick-up (from 1 to 365)
  • pickup_wday: Day of the week of the pick-up (from 1 to 7)
  • length_time: Duration of the ride (in seconds)
  • pickup_BoroCode: Macro-area of the pick-up
  • pickup_NTACode: Micro-area of the pick-up (Neighborhood Tabulation Areas)
  • dropoff_BoroCode: Macro-area of the drop-off
  • dropoff_NTACode: Micro-area of the drop-off (Neighborhood Tabulation Areas)
  • pickup_longitude: Longitude of the pick-up
  • pickup_latitude: Latitude of the pick-up
  • dropoff_longitude: Longitude of the drop-off
  • dropoff_latitude: Latitude of the drop-off
  • vendor_id: The TPEP provider that provided the record
  • passenger_count: The number of passengers in the vehicle. This is a driver-entered value.
  • trip_distance: The elapsed trip distance in miles reported by the taximeter
  • fare_amount: The time-and-distance fare calculated by the meter
  • pair: Combination of the variables pickup_NTACode and dropoff_NTACode

Import the data

You can download the data from the https://data-science-challenges.unibocconi.it platform or use the following code.

# Import basic libraries
import pandas as pd

taxi = pd.read_csv("https://datasciencebocconi.github.io/Data/taxi_train.csv")

taxi_pred = pd.read_csv("https://datasciencebocconi.github.io/Data/taxi_test.csv")

Submit a prediction

We implement a simple model (linear model) to illustrate how to submit your prediction.

# Consider here a couple of variables variable
X = taxi[['pickup_hour', 'trip_distance']]
X_pred  = taxi_pred[['pickup_hour', 'trip_distance']]

# Here, we create the numeric outcome
y = taxi["response"]
# Import a naive Bayes function
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

# Fit a naive Bayes Classifier
m_lin = LinearRegression()

# Fit the logistic regression model
m_lin.fit(X, y)

# Predict values on the prediction set
y_lin_pred = m_lin.predict(X_pred)
y_lin_pred
array([2.7989361 , 2.76085433, 2.88598095, ..., 2.82069711, 2.84245829,
       2.86965952])

Once we obtain a vector of numeric values based on the test set, we must save the vector into a .txt file.

export_pred = pd.DataFrame(y_lin_pred, columns = ['response'])

# The header and the index are removed as this is required by the platform
export_pred.to_csv('lin_pred.txt', index = False, header = False)

Look for the lin_pred.txt file created on your computer and download it from Google Colab. Of course, you can name the file as you wish, perhaps with a name that reminds you of the chosen method.

Then, you can upload the file to the platform https://data-science-challenges.unibocconi.it and see how you scored on the partial leaderboard.
